<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :funny --><img src=http://pages.prodigy.net/bestsmileys1/signs/Funny_post.gif ALT=":funny"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
The fact of the matter is that Sadham and all his top people have vanished without trace! It may yet be the case that they were all killed in the restaurant bombing. But I would be a little bit surprised that Sauron (Yes I think I’ll call him Sauron, I’ll say why later) would put himself in that danger given what has happened before. What he is certainly capable of doing though is rounding up all his top peoples doubles and setting them up in order to throw the US off guard!<br>
<br>
It is easy to forget just how nasty these people are and what they are capable of! That is one of the reasons why, thus far, they have outwitted us.<br>
<br>
As to whether we have won or not, It was my understanding that the war had two aims. <br>
<br>
1)It was a war against Saddham and his Ba’ath party cronies<br>
<br>
2)It was a war to liberate Iraq from them.<br>
<br>
Currently we are part way through both objectives but to my mind we have not yet achieved either of them.<br>
<br>
Objective one will only have been achieved (in my mind) when we either capture Sadham, the Chemical Brothers and the other cronies or we find hard evidence (IE That which would convince the most sceptical Arab fanatic) of their deaths!<br>
<br>
Objective two will only have been achieved when the last foreign soldier departs Iraq leaving behind a benign, popular government and a healthy economy (It doesn’t necessarily have to be a western style liberal democracy BTW)<br>
<br>
Objective two is some way off; the campaign is nowhere near being over. Objective one may never be achieved (though if they are currently all holed up in Tekrit then we have a good chance) <br>
<br>
If we do not achieve “one” then, as has been suggested elsewhere, Sadham could assume a ghostly Bin-Ladin presence and provide a rallying point for those that hate the west even more than Sadhams atrocities (Believe me! They are out there!)<br>
<br>
He will be portrayed as an Arab hero who stood up to the mighty USA and though, militarily defeated, he was, nevertheless, wily as a desert fox and eluded capture by the “Great Satan” to fight another day<br>
<br>
We wont have truly defeated him until he is dead or captured! (Preferably captured)<br>
<br>
On a lighter note!<br>
<br>
Why do I respect the information minister?<br>
<br>
Well, He managed to keep a straight face while spouting all that @#%$, He should have gone to Hollywood, he’d have made a much better living. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rollin --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/roll.gif ALT=":rollin"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Why Sauron? <br>
<br>
Iraqis actually call Iraq “Uruk”. If we have Sadham as the “Dark Lord” then his soldiers are the “Urukai” <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :jedi --><img src=http://www.smilies-world.de/Smilies/Smilies_boese_1/lsabre.gif ALT=":jedi"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Also, I was reminded,last week, that I was actually at school with the son of Tariq Aziz, so in terms of “Degrees of Separation” I am therefore certainly a “Two” to the Dark Lord, possibly even a “One” since I might have bumped into Tariq at an open day or some other time. Isn’t it a wonderful testament to the British public school system, It seems many of the worlds recent dictators and/or their staff have been to a British public school, Sandhurst or both!<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rofl --><img src=http://pages.prodigy.net/rogerlori1/emoticons/rofl.gif ALT=":rofl"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rofl --><img src=http://pages.prodigy.net/rogerlori1/emoticons/rofl.gif ALT=":rofl"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rofl --><img src=http://pages.prodigy.net/rogerlori1/emoticons/rofl.gif ALT=":rofl"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
To finish on a more serious note. I would be inclined to regard cheering crowds with a pinch of salt. They are a welcome sight since their presence makes the war easier to sell worldwide, particularly in the Arab world. However it should be remembered that Sadham had many enemies who he oppressed viciously, these people would certainly now be cheering. But he also had his supporters, these will either be keeping their heads down in their homes or trying to mingle with the jubilant crowds. (Like all the people in post war Germany who denied ever supporting the Nazis) <br>
<br>
Even worse, given the preparedness of fighters to use suicide bombing as a tactic I would be reluctant to let anybody ride on my tank just yet! <br>
<br>
